e system’s biological and sociocultural roots. Key components of the book are a thorough analysis of the assumptions underlying different perspectives on problems related to food and agriculture around the world and a discussion of alternative solutions. David Cleveland argues that combining selected aspects of small-scale traditional agriculture with modern scientific agriculture can help balance our biological need for food with its environmental impact—and continue to fulfill cultural, social, and psychological needs related to food. Balancing on a Planet is based on Cleveland’s research and engaging teaching about food and agriculture for more than three decades. It is a tool to help students, faculty, researchers, and interested readers understand debates about the current crisis and alternatives for the future.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAgricultural industriesxEnvironmental aspects. 0aFood industry and trade. 0aFood supply. 0aSustainable agriculturexEconomic aspects. 7aTechnology & Engineering / Agriculture / General.2bisacsh  aagriculture.  aagrifood system.  abreeders.  acooking.  acountry life.  aengaging.  aenvironmental impact.  afarm life.  afarms and farmers.  afood and ag.  afood lovers.  afood studies.  afood writing.  afood.  agastronomy.  aglobal agrifood.  ainterdisciplinary primer.  anatural settings.  apolitics.  arural.  ascientific agriculture.  asociocultural roots.  atechnology engineering.  athorough analysis.  atraditional agriculture.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052027742740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095708440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520957084423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9